The core principles are as follows: 

1.Learn Technologies one topic  at a time, its not all or nothing.

2.Instead, focus on core functionality- the things you will actually need to learn.

3.Learn new features and functions as you need them. 

4.Linking what you learn to real world use cases helps retention. 

5.If you are learning something new, try to integrate it into your workflow. 

6.Whenever possible, try to combine the tools you are learning into one solution.

7.Example workflow: Create notes with vim, then sync them to git repository while learning tmux on distro you are learning.

8.Your Passion project should be related to linux and most importantly -  fun!

9.Passion projects adds benefits to (and reinforces) your learning.

10.Choose your specialities-  You will end up getting exposed to various linux - related technologies.

11.Passion projects will help you avoid burnout -and thats important

12.You can't learn everything and thats okay!

13.Start with basics and then add additional skills as needed.

14.To help you keep track,create a personel learning track. 

15.Your interests will change over time and thats normal.

16. The history cmd can save you a ton of time, so definately learn it.

17.By default, all of the commands you enter are stored in your shell history.

18. Its especially useful for work - you can easily view past fixes and tweaks.
